  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the difference between L1 and L2 regularization? When does each perform better?",
  "response_text": "L1 and L2 regularization are two types of regularization techniques used in machine learning to prevent overfitting in models. The primary difference between them lies in the way they penalize the model's complexity.\n\n**L1 Regularization (Lasso Regression):**\n\nL1 regularization, also known as Lasso regression, adds a term to the loss function that is proportional to the absolute value of the model's coefficients. This term is often denoted as λ * |w|, where λ is the regularization strength and w is the model's coefficient. The L1 term encourages the model to set some of the coefficients to zero, effectively performing feature selection. This is because the absolute value function |w| is non-differentiable at zero, making it more likely for the model to set the coefficient to zero when the regularization strength is high.\n\n**L2 Regularization (Ridge Regression):**\n\nL2 regularization, also known as Ridge regression, adds a term to the loss function that is proportional to the square of the model's coefficients. This term is often denoted as λ * w^2, where λ is the regularization strength and w is the model's coefficient. The L2 term encourages the model to reduce the magnitude of all coefficients, but does not set any of them to zero.\n\n**When to use each:**\n\n1.  **L1 Regularization (Lasso Regression):**\n    *   Use when you have a large number of features and want to perform feature selection.\n    *   Use when you want to identify the most important features and eliminate the least important ones.\n    *   Use when you have a sparse data set, where most of the features are irrelevant.\n2.  **L2 Regularization (Ridge Regression):**\n    *   Use when you have a small number of features and want to prevent overfitting.\n    *   Use when you want to reduce the magnitude of all coefficients, but still want to use all features.\n    *   Use when you have a dense data set, where most of the features are relevant.\n\nIn summary, L1 regularization is useful for feature selection and sparse data sets, while L2 regularization is useful for preventing overfitting and dense data sets.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
